## Frequently Asked Questions

### Can I use kiro-agents in my commercial product?

Yes, under three options:
1. Use under AGPL-3.0 (must share your source code)
2. Purchase a Commercial License (no sharing required)
3. Wait 16 months and use under MIT (no restrictions)

### What happens if I violate the AGPL-3.0?

Your license terminates automatically. You must:
- Stop using the software immediately
- Remove all copies from your systems
- May face copyright infringement claims

### Can I fork kiro-agents?

Yes! Forks are encouraged when:
- You need incompatible technical changes
- Original project rejects your proposal after discussion
- You want to take the project in a different direction

Please:
- Keep the AGPL-3.0 license (or wait for MIT)
- Attribute the original project
- Consider contributing upstream when possible

### What if the project becomes unmaintained?

See CONTRIBUTING.md for our succession plan. In summary:
- Active forks can request ownership transfer
- After extended inactivity, project may be relicensed to public domain
- Community can continue development

### Why 16 months instead of 12?

This timeframe:
- Gives recent versions strong protection
- Allows sufficient time for commercial value
- Ensures code is mature and stable before MIT release
- Balances protection with eventual freedom

